# Purchase Order Management

## Overview

Purchase order management is the first stage of the wholesale order lifecycle. It involves receiving, reviewing, and preparing purchase orders before they enter internal order processing systems.

Wholesale businesses receive purchase orders from retail partners, distributors, or marketplaces through various channels including EDI integrations, retailer portals, and manual submission.

Proper purchase order management ensures that orders are captured accurately and routed into the operational workflow without errors.

---

## Common Purchase Order Sources

Wholesale organizations typically receive purchase orders through several channels:

• EDI integrations  
• retailer vendor portals  
• wholesale sales platforms  
• manual sales entry  

Each channel requires processes to ensure orders are captured consistently.

---

## Key Purchase Order Data

A purchase order typically contains the following information:

• retailer or distributor name  
• purchase order number  
• SKU or product identifiers  
• quantities ordered  
• agreed pricing  
• requested delivery date  
• shipping location  

Operations teams must ensure this information is complete before the order enters the processing pipeline.

---

## Operational Responsibilities

Purchase order management responsibilities often include:

• monitoring incoming orders  
• verifying required fields  
• confirming retailer identification  
• validating order formatting  
• routing orders to validation teams  

This stage acts as the intake gateway for all wholesale orders.

---

## Risks and Common Issues

Common purchase order intake issues include:

• missing SKU identifiers  
• incorrect pricing  
• incomplete shipping information  
• duplicate orders  
• formatting errors from integrations  

Early detection prevents downstream operational disruptions.

---

## Importance of Standardization

Standardized intake procedures ensure that all orders follow the same review process before moving to validation and processing stages.

This improves operational efficiency and reduces order errors.
